Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces. Remove the ends from the @carrot{1} (no need to peel), halve lengthways and then chop into 1cm wide long strips. Chop into 1cm chunks. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pour the boiling @water for the stock{650%ml} into a #pan{}, stir in the @red wine stock paste{28%g}, pop on medium-high heat and bring to the boil and stir until dissolved. Reduce the heat to low and leave the stock to keep warm. Meanwhile, heat a large wide-bottomed #saucepan{} or a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). When hot, add the @lamb mince{200%g} and cook until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Break it up with a #wooden spoon{} as it cooks.

Once browned, add the onion and carrot, stir and cook until the veg have softened, ~{5-6%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Add the garlic and cook, stirring for ~{1%minute} and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Stir in the @Arborio rice{175%g} and cook until the rice is translucent at the edges, ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir through the @tomato passata{1} and bring to the boil and reduce to a simmer until the liquid has been absorbed, ~{2%minutes}.

Next, stir in a ladle of your stock. When the stock has been absorbed by the rice, stir in another ladle of stock. Keep the pan on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time. It should take about ~{20-25%minutes} to cook and your risotto is done when your rice is 'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

If the risotto isn't quite cooked but the stock has been absorbed, simply add a splash of water and keep cooking until the rice is tender. Once the risotto is cooked, remove from the heat. Add the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}, @unsalted butter{30%g} and three-quarters of the parsley. Stir vigorously until everything is melted and combined.

Taste the risotto and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it. Serve in #bowls{} with the remaining parsley sprinkled on top and enjoy!